During a press briefing in Vietnam, Secretary of State John Kerry provided an update on President Obama's visit to Vietnam and reflected on the progress made in US-Vietnam relations. He highlighted the shift from thinking of Vietnam as a country of conflict to a country of opportunity and praised Vietnam's progress in practicing capitalism. Kerry also discussed the lifting of the lethal weapons ban, emphasizing that it signifies a normal relationship between the two countries and enables Vietnam to defend itself. He acknowledged that there are still differences between the US and Vietnam, particularly in terms of governance and human rights, but noted the importance of ongoing dialogue and progress. Kerry also addressed concerns about China's reaction to the US-Vietnam relationship, stating that the US is focused on promoting a rules-based order and peaceful resolution of conflicts in the South China Sea. The press briefing also touched on topics such as the battle against ISIS, the EgyptAir crash, and the level of instability in North Korea.